<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Lets see I could one.... Farm fucking bears all day for pelts, and make stupid n00b shit, to get 1 point better in a tradeskill,<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->In DAoC, you buy raw materials from NPC merchants conveniently located right next to the forge. <br>
<br>
A common fault of EQ players who bag on upcoming games that I have noticed is this: they tend to equate all actions or processes in upcoming games to how they are performed in EQ. Like the above example; you're assuming too much. You're assuming that tradeskills in EQ2 will be identical to tradeskills in EQ, and then bitching about it. It's ignorant. Why don't you let them publish the game before you rant about a process that exists only in your imagination? Who knows? Tradeskills might end up being a BLAST in EQ2.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Raids with guildies/killing/phat lewtz=fun<br>
<br>
Tradeskills=suxxorage<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I share this opinion as it applies to EQ and DAoC. But it's just a fucking opinion, not gospel. Lots of people who play EQ, DAoC, and other games fucking LOVE tradeskills. They love them as much as we hate them. Smart developers will cater to this. It's good for the game.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  this degrading weapons thing in EQ2 is retarded... So what your telling me is after the whole guild masses to slay some giant dragon, the uber sword that drops, I am going to have to learn a trade skill just to keep it from breaking... Thats sooo lame.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Again, how can you say the degrading process is lame until ou've exerienced it yourself and made a decision based on first-hand information? Stop spewing ignorance! It could turn out cooler than you'd ever imagined. Don't you think weapons and armor had to be maintained in the real world? Cared for so they don't rust away, or fail at a critical moment in combat? Yes, they did. Be aware: items in an environment where gear needs to be maintenanced will have - individually - less significance than your Palladius' Axe of Slaughter. It will be more like DAoC, where specific items don't matter as much as making sure your gear is appropriate to your level. I'm sure cool quests will exist, and cool items will abound, but whether you have cool item A or B will be irrelevant. Consider - think - about what a pain in the ass it was to get your epic, especially when you were competing with other players for the same drops. It wasn't very fun, was it? In a degrading gear environment, such competitions will be irrelevant. <br>
<br>
And finally...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  EQ2 is going to be the biggest timesink in the history of mmorgs...fuck that.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Here's what Bill Trost has to say about that:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  GameSpy: Are you moving away from the heavy combat oriented gameplay?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Bill: That will depend upon your individual play style and class choice, but yes there will be methods of earning experience within EverQuest II that have nothing to do with fighting and killing monsters.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Gamespy: How are the old issues of camping, training, downtime etc. being addressed?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Bill: We are taking steps to ensure that EverQuest II is a consistently enjoyable experience. Will camping exist? Probably, for those who enjoy it, but it certainly will not be the necessity that many view it as in EverQuest. Trains? No. We intend on eliminating trains, as much as we can, without lobotomizing our NPCs. Downtime? Our goals are to greatly reduce the amount of downtime across the board. Time spent playing the game should be spent PLAYING THE GAME.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Based on those commments, I'd be surprised if the timesinks were greater than in EQ. <br>
